[4] Florida (Duval County)
Date: Mon 14 Oct 2019, 2:55 PM
Source: CBS 47 Action Jax News [abridged, edited]
https://tinyurl.com/y3t975c4


The Florida Department of Health has confirmed 1 case of measles in a child who was not vaccinated in Duval County.

Health officials told Action News Jax a local hospital reported the case and then they stepped in and started an investigation. "In doing that, we were able to kind of map out the steps the family went through and where the child may have visited, and we contacted those places directly to make them aware that folks that visited those facilities may have been exposed," said Dr. Pauline Rolle, the Department of Health Medical Director for Duval County.

"Children, particularly for measles, mumps, or rubella, need to be vaccinated between 12 months and 15 months of age and again at 4 to 6 years of age," said Dr. Rolle.

Measles can result in hospitalizations, pneumonia and skin infections, which is why Brenna and Cory said they take all necessary precautions including getting their children vaccinated.

[Byline: Alicia Tarancon]

